   "source": [
    "# Notebook 11 — Phylogenetic Trees: UPGMA\n",
    "\n",
    "**Module:** 08 — Bioinformatics: Sequence Analysis  \n",
    "**Notebook:** 11 of 18  \n",
    "**Time estimate:** 60 minutes\n",
    "\n",
    "> UPGMA and NJ are the two must-know distance-based tree methods.\n",
    "> UPGMA is simpler but assumes a molecular clock. Know when this assumption fails."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Step 1 — Motivation\n",
    "\n",
    "Given a pairwise distance matrix from an MSA, how do you reconstruct the evolutionary\n",
    "tree? UPGMA (Unweighted Pair Group Method with Arithmetic Mean) is the simplest\n",
    "algorithm: greedily merge the two closest sequences, update the distance matrix,\n",
    "repeat until one node remains."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Step 2 — Intuition\n",
    "\n",
    "UPGMA: always merge the two closest things.\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Find the minimum distance pair $(i, j)$ in the matrix\n",
    "2. Create a new internal node with branch lengths $D[i,j]/2$ to each\n",
    "3. Replace $i$ and $j$ with the new node; update distances (arithmetic mean to all others)\n",
    "4. Repeat until one node remains\n",
    "\n",
    "The key assumption: all taxa evolve at the same rate (molecular clock). This produces\n",
    "an **ultrametric tree** where all tips are equidistant from the root.\n",
    "\n",
    "When the clock fails, UPGMA misplaces the root and may produce wrong topologies."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Step 3 — Biological Background\n",
    "\n",
    "UPGMA was developed for taxonomy before molecular data existed. For molecular data,\n",
    "the molecular clock assumption is rarely exactly true — different lineages evolve at\n",
    "different rates. In such cases, Neighbour-Joining (NB12) is preferred.\n",
    "\n",
    "When is UPGMA acceptable?\n",
    "- Comparing very closely related sequences (same gene, same species)\n",
    "- Constructing guide trees for MSA (where topology precision is less critical)\n",
    "- When you've explicitly verified a molecular clock (using a relative rate test — see Module 06)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Step 4 — Mathematical Explanation\n",
    "\n",
    "**UPGMA algorithm:**\n",
    "\n",
    "Given distance matrix $D$ and cluster sizes $n_i$ for each cluster $i$:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Find $(i,j)$ such that $D[i,j] = \\min_{k \\neq l} D[k,l]$\n",
    "2. Create internal node $u$ with branch lengths:\n",
    "   $$b_i = b_j = \\frac{D[i,j]}{2}$$\n",
    "3. Compute distance from new cluster $u$ to all other clusters $k$:\n",
    "   $$D[u,k] = \\frac{n_i \\cdot D[i,k] + n_j \\cdot D[j,k]}{n_i + n_j}$$\n",
    "   (weighted average, proportional to cluster size — this is the \"unweighted\" part:\n",
    "   unweighted means individual sequences are equally weighted)\n",
    "4. Remove $i$ and $j$; add $u$ with $n_u = n_i + n_j$\n",
    "5. Repeat until one node remains\n",
    "\n",
    "**Ultrametric property:** For any three taxa $a, b, c$: $D[a,c] \\leq \\max(D[a,b], D[b,c])$.\n",
    "This is equivalent to all taxa being equidistant from the root — the molecular clock."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Step 6 — Python Implementation\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from dataclasses import dataclass, field\n",
    "from typing import Optional\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "@dataclass\n",
    "class TreeNode:\n",
    "    name: str\n",
    "    left: Optional['TreeNode'] = None\n",
    "    right: Optional['TreeNode'] = None\n",
    "    left_dist: float = 0.0\n",
    "    right_dist: float = 0.0\n",
    "    height: float = 0.0  # distance from root to this node\n",
    "\n",
    "    def is_leaf(self):\n",
    "        return self.left is None and self.right is None\n",
    "\n",
    "    def to_newick(self) -> str:\n",
    "        if self.is_leaf():\n",
    "            return self.name\n",
    "        left_str = self.left.to_newick()\n",
    "        right_str = self.right.to_newick()\n",
    "        return f'({left_str}:{self.left_dist:.4f},{right_str}:{self.right_dist:.4f})'\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def upgma(dist_matrix: np.ndarray, names: list[str]) -> TreeNode:\n",
    "    n = len(names)\n",
    "    D = dist_matrix.copy().astype(float)\n",
    "    nodes = [TreeNode(name=name) for name in names]\n",
    "    sizes = [1] * n\n",
    "    active = list(range(n))\n",
    "    heights = [0.0] * n  # current height of each active node\n",
    "\n",
    "    while len(active) > 1:\n",
    "        # Find minimum distance pair among active nodes\n",
    "        min_d = float('inf')\n",
    "        min_i, min_j = -1, -1\n",
    "        for a in range(len(active)):\n",
    "            for b in range(a + 1, len(active)):\n",
    "                i, j = active[a], active[b]\n",
    "                if D[i, j] < min_d:\n",
    "                    min_d = D[i, j]\n",
    "                    min_i, min_j = i, j\n",
    "\n",
    "        # New internal node\n",
    "        new_height = min_d / 2\n",
    "        new_node = TreeNode(\n",
    "            name=f'({nodes[min_i].name},{nodes[min_j].name})',\n",
    "            left=nodes[min_i],\n",
    "            right=nodes[min_j],\n",
    "            left_dist=new_height - heights[min_i],\n",
    "            right_dist=new_height - heights[min_j],\n",
    "            height=new_height\n",
    "        )\n",
    "\n",
    "        # Allocate new index\n",
    "        new_idx = max(max(active) + 1, n)\n",
    "        # Expand D if necessary\n",
    "        if new_idx >= D.shape[0]:\n",
    "            new_D = np.zeros((new_idx + 1, new_idx + 1))\n",
    "            new_D[:D.shape[0], :D.shape[1]] = D\n",
    "            D = new_D\n",
    "            nodes.append(None)\n",
    "            sizes.append(0)\n",
    "            heights.append(0.0)\n",
    "\n",
    "        nodes[new_idx] = new_node\n",
    "        sizes[new_idx] = sizes[min_i] + sizes[min_j]\n",
    "        heights[new_idx] = new_height\n",
    "\n",
    "        # Update distances\n",
    "        for k in active:\n",
    "            if k == min_i or k == min_j:\n",
    "                continue\n",
    "            ni, nj = sizes[min_i], sizes[min_j]\n",
    "            new_d = (ni * D[min_i, k] + nj * D[min_j, k]) / (ni + nj)\n",
    "            D[new_idx, k] = new_d\n",
    "            D[k, new_idx] = new_d\n",
    "\n",
    "        # Update active list\n",
    "        active.remove(min_i)\n",
    "        active.remove(min_j)\n",
    "        active.append(new_idx)\n",
    "\n",
    "    return nodes[active[0]]\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Test with classic example\n",
    "# Distance matrix for 4 taxa (known tree: ((A,B),(C,D)))\n",
    "names_test = ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D']\n",
    "D_test = np.array([\n",
    "    [0, 2, 4, 4],\n",
    "    [2, 0, 4, 4],\n",
    "    [4, 4, 0, 2],\n",
    "    [4, 4, 2, 0],\n",
    "], dtype=float)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Distance matrix:\")\n",
    "print(D_test)\n",
    "print()\n",
    "\n",
    "tree = upgma(D_test, names_test)\n",
    "print(f\"UPGMA tree (Newick): {tree.to_newick()}\")\n",
    "print(\"Expected: ((A,B),(C,D)) — each with branch length 1.0\")"
   ]
  },
  {
